 The City Diary
																																																																																		Two persons were arrested at Calcutta airport on Monday on charges of travelling with forged passports. Deepak Bhai Bhaktidas Patel and Hansaben Pravin Kumar, who claimed to be husband and wife, went from Calcutta to Frankfurt on October 26. However, immigration officials at Frankfurt sent them back to Calcutta for carrying forged passports. During interrogation, the couple told immigration officials that they were residents of Gujarat and had planned to go to Toronto. They had managed to get the forged passports from an Ahmedabad-based travel agent. Immigration officials said they were probing how the couple got to board the flight from Calcutta with forged passports.																																																		An unidentified man, around 40 years old, was killed by a private bus on DL Khan Road, near Alipore bridge, around 4.20pm on Monday. Police said the man was on a bicycle. The bus knocked him down and sped away.																																																								n unknown vehicle hit a man, about 45 years old, at the crossing of MG Road and Chittaranjan Avenue around 6.15pm on Monday. He was rushed to Medical College and Hospital. The man is yet to be identified.																																																		Veteran actor Soumitra Chatterjee was discharged on Monday afternoon from Rabindranath Tagore International Institute of Cardiac Sciences. A hospital official said Chatterjee had recovered completely. He will, however, require regular check-ups.																																																		Anil Kundu, 72, a resident of Gokul Boral Street, in Muchipara, committed suicide by hanging himself from the ceiling of his room on Monday. Police said a suicide note was found near the body, which was sent for post-mortem. A preliminary investigation suggested that Kundu had been suffering from depression for some time. 																																																		A fire broke out at Jessop Building, on Canning Street, around 12.18pm on Monday, police said. The building houses several offices and more than 200 people were evacuated after the fire broke out in an electrical junction box on the ground floor. Three fire tenders brought the blaze under control by 12.40pm. No one was injured.																																																		Two constables were seriously injured and had to be hospitalised after the van they were travelling in met with an accident near GD island, in Salt Lake, on Monday afternoon. According to police, a rear wheel of the van came off.																																																		There was a flutter at Agarpara railway station, on the northern fringes of the city, on Monday evening after passengers spotted an abandoned girl child near platform 1. Police said the baby, about seven days old, was found in a plastic bag under a tree. It has been sent to Sagar Dutta Hospital.							TO LIONS CLUB OF CALCUTTA (TOLLYGUNGE) for installing two tubewells in Amta 
